.SH Overview
.SS The Four Repositories
The gloat ecosystem consists of four interconnected repositories:
.IP "  1." 5
\fBgloathub/gloat\fP — The AOT (Ahead-of-Time) compiler
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Converts YAMLScript, Clojure, or Glojure source files to Go code
.IP \(bu 2
Provides the YS standard library as a Go module (\fBys/pkg\fR)
.IP \(bu 2
Generates buildable Go directories or compiled binaries
.RE
.IP "  2." 5
\fBglojurelang/glojure\fP — Glojure compiler/runtime used by Gloat
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Provides the \fBglj\fR compiler and REPL
.IP \(bu 2
Includes support for Go code generation and broad cross-compilation
.IP \(bu 2
Fixes for issues like \fBseqable?\fR handling
.RE
.IP "  3." 5
\fBmakeplus/makes\fP — Makefile-based dependency and build system
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Auto-bootstraps all tool dependencies
.IP \(bu 2
Provides \fB\&.mk\fR modules for gloat, glojure, go, yamlscript, etc.
.IP \(bu 2
Installs everything under \fB\&.cache/\fR (no global pollution)
.IP \(bu 2
Powers both gloat itself and downstream projects
.RE
.IP "  4." 5
\fBingydotnet/gist\fP — Flagship downstream project
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Demonstrates the full gloat toolchain in action
.IP \(bu 2
Uses Makes for dependency management
.IP \(bu 2
Publishes both source and compiled \fBgo/\fR directory
.IP \(bu 2
Cross-platform binary releases via GitHub
.RE

.SS The Compilation Pipeline
The gloat compiler orchestrates a multi-stage transformation:

.EX
YAMLScript (.ys) → Clojure (.clj) → Glojure (.glj) → Go (.go) → Binary/WASM
.EE

.PP
Each stage is handled by a specialized tool:
- \fBYS → CLJ\fP: YAMLScript compiler (from yamlscript repo)
- \fBCLJ → GLJ\fP: Glojure's rewrite script (transforms Clojure idioms)
- \fBGLJ → GO\fP: Glojure compiler (generates Go loader files)
- \fBGO → BIN\fP: Go toolchain (builds native executables)

.SS How Makes Bootstraps Dependencies
Makes uses a 2-line Makefile preamble that clones itself into \fB\&.cache/makes/\fR:

.EX
M := .cache/makes
$(shell [ -d $M ] || git clone -q https://github.com/makeplus/makes $M)
.EE

.PP
All tool dependencies are then declared via \fBinclude\fR directives, and Makes
handles automatic installation on first use.
Users are prompted interactively before the first installation.

.SH Repository Layout
.SS Key Directories in gloat
.EX
gloat/
├── bin/
│   └── gloat              # Bash wrapper (sets GLOAT_VERSION, PATH)
├── src/                   # Babashka source files
│   └── gloat.clj          # Main Babashka script (CLI logic)
├── template/
│   ├── clojure.clj        # Template for YS→CLJ conversion
│   ├── go.mod             # Template for generated Go modules
│   ├── main.go            # Template for binary entry point
│   ├── lib-main.go        # Template for shared library entry point
│   └── Makefile           # Template for generated Go directories
├── ys/                    # YS standard library (multi-stage build)
│   ├── src/               # Clojure source files
│   │   ├── yamlscript/    # Upstream YS code (util, common)
│   │   └── ys/            # Gloat-specific YS runtime (v0, std, fs, etc.)
│   ├── glj/               # Glojure intermediate files
│   ├── go/                # Compiled Go loader files
│   ├── pkg/               # Published Go module (sync from go/)
│   │   ├── go.mod         # ys/pkg Go module definition
│   │   └── all/           # Umbrella package for easy import
│   └── patch/             # Patches for babashka compatibility
├── common/
│   └── common.mk          # Version overrides (GLOJURE-VERSION, etc.)
├── util/                  # Helper scripts (getopt, etc.)
└── Makefile               # Build system (YS-PKG-VERSION, targets)
.EE

.SS The \fBys/\fR Subtree: Multi-Stage Build
The YS standard library undergoes a three-stage build process:
.IP "  1." 5
\fB\fBys/src/\fR\fP — Clojure source files
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\fByamlscript/\fR — Synced from upstream yamlscript repo (util, common)
.IP \(bu 2
\fBys/\fR — Gloat-specific runtime (v0, std, fs, ipc, json, http, dwim)
.RE
.IP "  2." 5
\fB\fBys/glj/\fR\fP — Glojure intermediate files
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Generated via \fBmake update\fR (runs rewrite.clj on each .clj file)
.RE
.IP "  3." 5
\fB\fBys/go/\fR\fP — Compiled Go loader files
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Generated via \fBmake update\fR (compiles each .glj to Go)
.IP \(bu 2
Structure: \fBys/go/namespace/path/loader.go\fR
.RE
.IP "  4." 5
\fB\fBys/pkg/\fR\fP — Published Go module
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Synced from \fBys/go/\fR via \fBmake ys-pkg\fR (excludes \fBall/\fR)
.IP \(bu 2
Tagged as a Go sub-module: \fBys/pkg/v0.1.0\fR
.IP \(bu 2
Includes \fBall/all.go\fR umbrella package
.RE

.SS Templates and Placeholders
Gloat uses templates in \fBtemplate/\fR with placeholder substitution:

.PP
\fBgo.mod template\fP (\fBtemplate/go.mod\fR):

.EX
module GO-MODULE

go 1.24

require (
	github.com/glojurelang/glojure GLOJURE-VERSION
	github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg YS-PKG-VERSION
)

replace github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg => GLOAT-ROOT/ys/pkg
.EE

.PP
Placeholders:
- \fBGO-MODULE\fR — Generated or user-specified module name
- \fBGLOJURE-VERSION\fR — From \fBcommon/common.mk\fR (e.g., \fBv0.6.5-rc4\fR)
- \fBYS-PKG-VERSION\fR — From \fBMakefile\fR (e.g., \fBv0.1.0\fR)
- \fBGLOAT-ROOT\fR — Absolute path to gloat repo
- \fBPACKAGE-PATH\fR — User namespace path (e.g., \fBfoo/core\fR)
- \fBNAMESPACE\fR — User namespace symbol (e.g., \fBfoo.core\fR)

.PP
The \fBreplace\fR directive enables local development by pointing to the gloat
repo's \fBys/pkg/\fR directory.
For published releases, this directive must be removed.

.PP
\fBmain.go template\fP (\fBtemplate/main.go\fR):

.EX
package main

import (
	_ "GO-MODULE/pkg/PACKAGE-PATH"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/all"
)
.EE

.PP
The umbrella import \fBys/pkg/all\fR loads all YS stdlib packages in one line
(instead of 9 individual imports).

.SH The Makes Build System
.SS How It Works
Makes is a dependency management system built on GNU Make.
It provides a collection of \fB\&.mk\fR modules that handle tool installation,
version management, and common build tasks.

.PP
\fBBootstrap Pattern\fP (2-line preamble in every Makefile):

.EX
M := .cache/makes
$(shell [ -d $M ] || git clone -q https://github.com/makeplus/makes $M)
.EE

.PP
This clones Makes into \fB\&.cache/makes/\fR if it doesn't exist.
All subsequent \fBinclude\fR directives load \fB\&.mk\fR modules from there.

.PP
\fBKey \fB\&.mk\fR Modules\fP:
- \fBinit.mk\fR — Initializes Makes variables and paths
- \fBgo.mk\fR — Installs and manages Go toolchain
- \fBglojure.mk\fR — Installs the Glojure compiler
- \fBbabashka.mk\fR — Installs Babashka (runs gloat.clj)
- \fByamlscript.mk\fR — Installs YAMLScript compiler
- \fBgloat.mk\fR — Provides \fBgloat-go\fR, \fBgloat-github-release\fR targets
- \fBgh.mk\fR — Installs GitHub CLI
- \fBclean.mk\fR — Provides clean/distclean targets
- \fBshell.mk\fR — Provides \fBmake shell\fR for running commands with tools

.PP
All tools are installed under \fB\&.cache/local/\fR:

.EX
\&.cache/
├── makes/                    # Makes repo (cloned)
│   ├── *.mk                  # Module definitions
│   └── share/                # Shared assets (configs, etc.)
└── local/
    ├── bin/                  # Tool binaries (bb, glj, go, ys, etc.)
    ├── go/                   # GOPATH
    ├── cache/                # Build caches
    └── gloat-VERSION/        # Cloned gloat repo (per version)
.EE

.SS Using Makes
\fBRun commands with project dependencies\fP:

.EX
make shell cmd='gloat --version'
make shell cmd='go version'
make shell cmd='which bb'
.EE

.PP
\fBList installed dependencies\fP:

.EX
make path-deps
.EE

.PP
\fBClean build artifacts\fP:

.EX
make clean       # Removes MAKES-CLEAN files
make distclean   # Also removes .cache/
.EE

.SS Version Management in Makes
Makes modules define version variables with \fB?=\fR (override-able defaults):

.EX
# From go.mk
GO-VERSION ?= 1.25.6
.EE

.PP
Projects override these in their own Makefile or \fBcommon/common.mk\fR using \fB:=\fR:

.EX
# From gloat's common/common.mk
GLOJURE-VERSION := 0.6.5-rc4
GLOJURE-COMMIT := gloat
GLOJURE-REPO := https://github.com/glojurelang/glojure
.EE

.PP
The \fB:=\fR operator has higher precedence than \fB?=\fR, so project values win.

.SH How Gloat Generates Output
.SS The \fBgloat -o dir/\fR Flow
When you run \fBgloat foo.ys -o build/\fR, gloat performs these steps:
.IP "  1." 5
\fBCompile user code\fP: YS → CLJ → GLJ → Go
.IP "  2." 5
\fBCopy GLJ stdlib\fP: Copies \fBys/glj/\fR tree to temp directory
.IP "  3." 5
\fBCompile all namespaces\fP: Runs \fBglj\fR to generate Go loader files
.IP "  4." 5
\fBFilter output\fP: Copies only user code from temp dir to \fBbuild/pkg/\fR
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Excludes \fByamlscript/\fR and \fBys/\fR paths (stdlib)
.IP \(bu 2
Stdlib comes from \fBys/pkg\fR module instead
.RE
.IP "  5." 5
\fBRender templates\fP: Generates \fBgo.mod\fR, \fBmain.go\fR, \fBMakefile\fR
.IP "  6." 5
\fBPopulate go.mod\fP:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Module name (auto-detected or user-specified)
.IP \(bu 2
Glojure version (from \fBcommon/common.mk\fR)
.IP \(bu 2
YS pkg version (from \fBMakefile\fR)
.IP \(bu 2
Replace directive (for local development)
.RE

.SS The \fBys/pkg\fR Go Module
The \fBys/pkg\fR directory is a Go module that publishes the YS standard library:

.PP
\fBStructure\fP:

.EX
ys/pkg/
├── go.mod                              # Go module definition
├── yamlscript/common/loader.go         # Loader for yamlscript.common
├── yamlscript/util/loader.go           # Loader for yamlscript.util
├── ys/dwim/loader.go                   # Loader for ys.dwim
├── ys/fs/loader.go                     # Loader for ys.fs
├── ys/http/loader.go                   # Loader for ys.http
├── ys/ipc/loader.go                    # Loader for ys.ipc
├── ys/json/loader.go                   # Loader for ys.json
├── ys/std/loader.go                    # Loader for ys.std
├── ys/v0/loader.go                     # Loader for ys.v0
└── all/all.go                          # Umbrella package
.EE

.PP
\fBThe Umbrella Import\fP (\fBys/pkg/all/all.go\fR):

.EX
package all

import (
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/yamlscript/common"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/yamlscript/util"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/dwim"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/fs"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/http"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/ipc"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/json"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/std"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/v0"
)
.EE

.PP
This allows generated code to import the entire stdlib with a single line:

.EX
import _ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/all"
.EE

.PP
\fBThe \fBreplace\fR Directive\fP (local development vs published):

.PP
During development, the generated \fBgo.mod\fR includes:

.EX
replace github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg => /abs/path/to/gloat/ys/pkg
.EE

.PP
This lets you iterate on stdlib changes without publishing.
For releases, this directive is stripped (see "Downstream Project Setup" below).

.SS Binary/WASM/Lib Output Modes
When generating binaries (\fB-o foo\fR, \fB-o foo.wasm\fR, \fB-o foo.so\fR):
.IP "  1." 5
\fBGenerate Go directory\fP in a temp location
.IP "  2." 5
\fBRun \fBgo mod tidy\fR\fP to fetch dependencies
.IP "  3." 5
\fBBuild with \fBgo build\fR\fP:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Binary: \fBgo build -ldflags "-s -w" -o foo main.go\fR
.IP \(bu 2
Library: \fBgo build -buildmode=c-shared -o foo.so main.go\fR
.IP \(bu 2
WASM: \fBGOOS=wasip1 GOARCH=wasm go build -o foo.wasm main.go\fR
.RE
.IP "  4." 5
\fBCopy output\fP to user-specified location
.IP "  5." 5
\fBClean up\fP temp directory

.PP
Cross-compilation uses \fB--platform=OS/ARCH\fR (e.g., \fBlinux/amd64\fR, \fBdarwin/arm64\fR).

.SH Downstream Project Setup
Downstream projects (like gist) use gloat via Makes to build and release
compiled binaries.

.SS Minimal Makefile
.EX
# Example: gist/Makefile

M := .cache/makes
$(shell [ -d $M ] || git clone -q https://github.com/makeplus/makes $M)

VERSION := 0.1.54
FILE := gist
GLOAT-RELEASE-WITH-GO-DIRECTORY := 1

include $M/init.mk
include $M/gloat.mk
.EE

.PP
\fBKey Variables\fP:
- \fBFILE\fR — The source file to compile (auto-detected if only one .ys/.clj)
  - Can omit extension (e.g., \fBFILE := gist\fR will auto-detect \fBgist.ys\fR)
- \fBVERSION\fR — The release version (used by \fBgloat-github-release\fR)
- \fBGLOAT-RELEASE-WITH-GO-DIRECTORY\fR — Set to \fB1\fR to include \fBgo/\fR in releases (for \fBgo install\fR)

.SS Platform Configuration
Create \fB\&.makes/gloat.config\fR to specify target platforms:

.EX
[gloat.platforms]
	name = linux/amd64
	name = linux/arm64
	name = darwin/amd64
	name = darwin/arm64
	name = windows/amd64
.EE

.PP
This configures which platforms are built during \fBmake gloat-bin\fR\&.

.SS The \fBgloat-go\fR Target
The \fBgloat-go\fR target (from \fBgloat.mk\fR) generates the \fBgo/\fR directory:

.EX
make gloat-go
.EE

.PP
\fBWhat it does\fP:
1. Runs \fBgloat FILE -o go/\fR to generate Go module
2. Rewrites module path from \fBgithub.com/gloathub/go\fR to the project's path
   (auto-detected from \fBgit remote get-url origin\fR)
3. Moves \fBmain.go\fR to \fBgo/cmd/BINARY-NAME/main.go\fR (Go convention)
4. Updates \fBgo/Makefile\fR with correct binary name
5. Runs \fBgo mod tidy\fR in \fBgo/\fR

.PP
\fBKey subtlety\fP: The current \fBgloat.mk\fR does NOT remove the \fBreplace\fR
directive.
This is fine for local development, but for published releases, the \fBreplace\fR
line must be stripped so \fBgo install\fR fetches \fBys/pkg\fR from the Go proxy.

.SS The \fBgloat-github-release\fR Target
The \fBgloat-github-release\fR target (from \fBgloat.mk\fR) automates the full release
process:

.EX
make gloat-github-release VERSION=0.1.5
.EE

.PP
\fBWhat it does\fP:
1. Updates \fBVERSION\fR in Makefile and source file
2. (If \fBGLOAT-RELEASE-WITH-GO-DIRECTORY\fR is set) Regenerates \fBgo/\fR directory
3. Commits changes: \fBgit commit -m 'Version v0.1.5'\fR
4. Tags release: \fBgit tag v0.1.5\fR
5. (If \fBGLOAT-RELEASE-WITH-GO-DIRECTORY\fR is set) Tags Go submodule: \fBgit tag go/v0.1.5\fR
6. Pushes code and tags: \fBgit push && git push --tags\fR
7. Builds binaries for all platforms (via \fBgloat-bin\fR)
8. Creates GitHub release with binaries attached

.SS How \fBgo install\fR Works
Once a project publishes its \fBgo/\fR directory with the correct module path
(and no \fBreplace\fR directive), users can install it via:

.EX
go install github.com/ingydotnet/gist/go/cmd/gist@v0.1.5
.EE

.PP
This works because:
1. The \fBgo/\fR directory is committed to the repo
2. The Go submodule tag \fBgo/v0.1.5\fR points to a commit with the correct \fBgo/go.mod\fR
3. The \fBgo.mod\fR requires \fBgithub.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg\fR (fetched from proxy)
4. No \fBreplace\fR directive interferes with module resolution

.SH Version Management
Gloat's version ecosystem has multiple moving parts.
All versions must be kept in sync for releases.

.SS All Version Locations
.IP "  1." 5
\fB\fBbin/gloat\fR\fP — Tool version (Bash wrapper)

.EX
export GLOAT_VERSION=0.1.0
.EE

.RS
.IP "  1." 5
\fB\fBcommon/common.mk\fR\fP — Glojure version
\fBmakefile
GLOJURE-VERSION := 0.6.5-rc4
GLOJURE-REPO := https://github.com/glojurelang/glojure
\fR
.RE
.IP "  2." 5
\fB\fBMakefile\fR\fP — YS pkg Go module version

.EX
YS-PKG-VERSION ?= v0.1.0
.EE

.RS
.IP "  1." 5
\fB\fBys/pkg/go.mod\fR\fP — Hardcoded Glojure dependency
\fBgo
require github.com/glojurelang/glojure v0.6.5-rc4
\fR
.RE
.IP "  3." 5
\fB\fBChanges\fR\fP — Release changelog
```yaml
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
version: 0.1.0
date:    Sun Feb  1 06:48:57 PM PST 2026
changes:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Initial release
\fB
### How Versions Propagate
Gloat uses `get-make-var` in `src/gloat.clj` to read Makefile variables:
\fRclojure
(def get-make-var
(memoize
(fn var-name
\[la]let [result (process/shell
       {:out :string}\[ra]")
       (str "print-" var-name))]
(str/trim (:out result))))))
```
.RE
.RE

.PP
This is called during template rendering:

.EX
(let [glojure-version (get-make-var "GLOJURE-VERSION")
      ys-pkg-version (get-make-var "YS-PKG-VERSION")
      result (render-template
              template-content
              [["GLOJURE-VERSION" glojure-version]
               ["YS-PKG-VERSION" ys-pkg-version]])]
  ...)
.EE

.PP
So:
- \fBcommon/common.mk\fR → \fBGLOJURE-VERSION\fR → \fBgo.mod\fR template
- \fBMakefile\fR → \fBYS-PKG-VERSION\fR → \fBgo.mod\fR template

.SS Go Module Tagging
Go uses version tags to identify module versions:

.PP
\fBMain module\fP (e.g., gloat itself):

.EX
git tag v0.1.0
.EE

.PP
\fBSub-module\fP (e.g., \fBys/pkg\fR):

.EX
git tag ys/pkg/v0.1.0
.EE

.PP
\fBGo sub-directory\fP (e.g., \fBgo/\fR in downstream projects):

.EX
git tag go/v0.1.5
.EE

.PP
The tag path corresponds to the module's location in the repo.

.SH The YS Standard Library
.SS Build Pipeline
The YS stdlib is built in multiple stages:
.IP "  1." 5
\fB\fBys/src/*.clj\fR\fP — Clojure source files
.IP "  2." 5
\fB\fBys/glj/*.glj\fR\fP — Glojure intermediate files (via \fBrewrite.clj\fR)
.IP "  3." 5
\fB\fBys/go/*/loader.go\fR\fP — Go loader files (via \fBglj\fR compiler)
.IP "  4." 5
\fB\fBys/pkg/\fR\fP — Published Go module (synced from \fBys/go/\fR)

.SS Build Targets
\fB\fBmake update\fR\fP — Rebuild all Go files from source:

.EX
make update
.EE

.PP
This runs the full pipeline: CLJ → GLJ → GO for all stdlib namespaces.

.PP
\fB\fBmake ys-pkg\fR\fP — Sync \fBys/go/\fR to \fBys/pkg/\fR and tidy:

.EX
make ys-pkg
.EE

.PP
This copies Go files to \fBys/pkg/\fR, excluding \fBall/\fR and go.mod/go.sum, then
runs \fBgo mod tidy\fR\&.

.PP
\fB\fBmake tag-ys-pkg\fR\fP — Create version tag:

.EX
make tag-ys-pkg YS-PKG-VERSION=0.1.0
.EE

.PP
This creates an annotated tag \fBys/pkg/v0.1.0\fR\&.

.SS The \fBys/pkg/all/all.go\fR Umbrella Package
The \fBall\fR package provides a convenience import for all stdlib packages:

.EX
package all

import (
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/yamlscript/common"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/yamlscript/util"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/dwim"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/fs"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/http"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/ipc"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/json"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/std"
	_ "github.com/gloathub/gloat/ys/pkg/ys/v0"
)
.EE

.PP
This is manually maintained (not auto-generated).
It's excluded from the \fBmake ys-pkg\fR sync to avoid overwriting it.

.SS Upstream Sync
Most YS stdlib files come from the upstream \fByaml/yamlscript\fR repo:
- \fByamlscript/util.clj\fR
- \fByamlscript/common.clj\fR

.PP
These are synced via:

.EX
make ys/src/yamlscript/util.clj    # Updates from upstream
.EE

.PP
Gloat-specific files (no upstream equivalents):
- \fBys/src/ys/v0.clj\fR — Main YS runtime
- \fBys/src/ys/fs.clj\fR — Go filesystem interop (not babashka.fs)
- \fBys/src/ys/ipc.clj\fR — Go IPC interop (not babashka.process)
- \fBys/src/ys/json.clj\fR — Pure Clojure JSON (not clojure.data.json)
- \fBys/src/ys/http.clj\fR — Go net/http wrapper (not babashka.http-client)

.SH Glojure Dependency
.SS Why Glojure?
Gloat depends on glojurelang/glojure for several reasons:
.IP "  1." 5
\fBGo compilation improvements\fP — Patches to improve generated Go code
.IP "  2." 5
\fBExtended platform support\fP — Adds 15-20 additional cross-compilation targets
.IP "  3." 5
\fBBug fixes\fP — Fixes for issues like \fBseqable?\fR handling in generated code
.IP "  4." 5
\fBStability\fP — Pins a known-good version with gloat-specific features

.SS Glojure Details
\fBRepository\fP: \fBglojurelang/glojure\fR
\fBConfigured in\fP: \fBcommon/common.mk\fR

.EX
GLOJURE-VERSION := 0.6.5-rc4
GLOJURE-REPO := https://github.com/glojurelang/glojure
GLOJURE-GET-URL := github.com/glojurelang/glojure/cmd/glj
.EE

.SS Upstream Sync
Gloat tracks tagged glojurelang/glojure releases and can use a local
Glojure checkout during development via \fBGLOJURE_DIR\fR or the workspace
helper targets.

.SH Development Workflow
.SS Initial Setup
\fBAdd gloat to PATH\fP:

.EX
cd /path/to/gloat
source .rc
.EE

.PP
The \fB\&.rc\fR file adds \fBbin/\fR to your PATH.

.PP
\fBFirst run installs dependencies\fP:

.EX
gloat --help
.EE

.PP
This prompts you to install dependencies (bb, glj, go, ys) into \fB\&.cache/local/\fR\&.
After installation, all tools are available via the PATH from \fBmake path\fR\&.

.SS Running Tests
\fBRun gloat test suite\fP:

.EX
make test           # Run prove tests
make test v=1       # Verbose test output
.EE

.PP
\fBRun tests in Docker\fP (clean environment):

.EX
make distclean      # Must clean first
make test-docker
.EE

.SS Modifying the Standard Library
\fBEdit a stdlib file\fP:

.EX
vim ys/src/ys/std.clj
.EE

.PP
\fBRebuild Go files\fP:

.EX
make update         # Regenerates ys/glj/ and ys/go/
.EE

.PP
\fBSync to published module\fP:

.EX
make ys-pkg         # Copies to ys/pkg/ and runs go mod tidy
.EE

.PP
\fBTest your changes\fP:

.EX
make test
.EE

.PP
\fBCommit the changes\fP:

.EX
git add ys/src/ys/std.clj ys/glj/ys/std.glj ys/go/ys/std/loader.go
git commit -m "Improve ys.std documentation"
.EE

.SS Typical Development Cycle
.IP "  1." 5
\fBMake changes\fP to gloat source (\fBsrc/gloat.clj\fR) or stdlib (\fBys/src/\fR)
.IP "  2." 5
\fBRun tests\fP to verify: \fBmake test\fR
.IP "  3." 5
\fBTest with example\fP project: \fBmake run FILE=demo/foo.ys\fR
.IP "  4." 5
\fBUpdate stdlib\fP if needed: \fBmake update && make ys-pkg\fR
.IP "  5." 5
\fBCommit changes\fP

.SS Working with Downstream Projects
\fBTest gloat changes with a downstream project\fP:

.EX
cd /path/to/gist
rm -rf .cache/makes     # Clear Makes cache
cd .cache
ln -s /path/to/gloat gloat-main   # Use local gloat
cd ..
make gloat-go           # Regenerate go/ with local gloat
.EE

.PP
This bypasses the git clone step in \fBgloat.mk\fR and uses your local gloat repo.

.ti 0
\l'\n(.lu'

.PP
This tutorial should provide a comprehensive understanding of how the gloat
ecosystem works.
For more specific information about release management, see \fBdoc/release-plan.md\fR\&.
